				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">British Construction Giant Carillion Drops Bid for Rival Balfour Beatty</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Chad Bray			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-08-20T08:30:28+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">August 20, 2014 4:30 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">August 20, 2014 4:30 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/08/20/balfour-beatty-rejects-latest-offer-from-rival-carillion/" data-title="British Construction Giant Carillion Drops Bid for Rival Balfour Beatty" data-description="After Balfour Beatty rejected the company&#039;s latest bid, Carillion decided to end its pursuit a day before a regulatory deadline to make a final offer or walk away for up to six months.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/08/20/business/dbpix-balfour-beatty/dbpix-balfour-beatty-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/08/20/business/dbpix-balfour-beatty/dbpix-balfour-beatty-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/08/20/business/dbpix-balfour-beatty/dbpix-balfour-beatty-blog480.jpg" id="100000003063265" width="480" height="320" alt="Tower cranes in central London in 2008."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="320"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Tower cranes in central London in 2008.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Shaun Curry/Agence France-Presse â Getty Images</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span id="t10h39s" class="update">Updated, 10:39 a.m. | </span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">LONDON â The British construction and services company Carillion said on Wednesday that it would abandon the pursuit of its rival Balfour Beatty after the company rejected its latest takeover approach.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The two companies had appeared close to a deal last month, but Balfour Beatty <a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/31/balfour-beatty-calls-off-merger-talks-with-rival-carillion/?_php=true&amp;_type=blogs&amp;_r=0">called off talks</a> after Carillion insisted that a Balfour-owned consulting business, Parsons Brinckerhoff, not be sold and remain part of any combined group. Balfour Beatty plans to sell the consulting business.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On Tuesday, Carillion <a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/08/19/british-construction-company-carillion-sweetens-offer-for-balfour-beatty/?_php=true&amp;_type=blogs&amp;module=BlogPost-Title&amp;version=Blog%20Main&amp;contentCollection=Mergers%20&amp;%20Acquisitions&amp;action=Click&amp;pgtype=Blogs&amp;region=Body&amp;_r=0">made a last-ditch pitch</a> to acquire its rival, offering to give Balfour Beatty shareholders control of the combined company and to pay them a cash dividend in a deal that valued Balfour Beatty at 2.1 billion pounds, or about $3.5 billion.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But Balfour Beatty said on Wednesday that Carillionâs latest offer had again failed to resolve its concerns about Parsons Brinckerhoff and the risks associated with Carillionâs proposed business plan, which includes reducing the scale of its British construction business just as the economy seems to be picking up.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Balfour Beatty also declined to ask regulators for permission to continue negotiations past a âput up or shut upâ deadline on Thursday, in which Carillion would have had to make a final offer or walk away for up to six months.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âCarillion therefore today announces that it is no longer pursuing such a merger,â the company said in a news release on Wednesday afternoon.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In making its final pitch, Carillion argued on Tuesday that its bid presented âa compelling caseâ for Balfour Beattyâs board of directors to request more time from regulators to continue talks.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Balfour Beattyâs board, however, closed the door on an extension on Wednesday and said it would pursue a strategy as a stand-alone company.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe board will also remain open to strategic value creating opportunities across the group while it concentrates on the restoration of value to its shareholders,â Balfour Beatty said. âIt will consider all such opportunities, and the risks associated with their execution, taking full account of the significant recovery potential within the Balfour Beatty business.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Shares of Balfour Beatty declined 6.7 percent, to Â£2.39, in afternoon trading in London on Wednesday, while Carillionâs shares were down 2 percent, to Â£3.30.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Under Carillionâs last proposal, Balfour Beatty shareholders would have owned 58.3 percent of the combined company and received cash dividends totaling Â£59 million.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Carillion previously said it thought that it could save at least Â£175 million a year by 2016 if the companies were to merge.  Balfour Beatty has disputed that figure, particularly as it is tied to a smaller construction business in Britain.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But the real sticking point had been an apparent change of heart by Carillion regarding Parsons Brinckerhoff.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Balfour Beatty said that Carillion initially agreed to let the separate sale of Parsons Brinckerhoff proceed but later changed course by insisting that the consulting business was pivotal to the deal.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In an effort to save deal, Carillion had offered to cover the costs of potential bidders for the consulting business in order to encourage them to remain in the process while Carillion and Balfour Beatty proceeded with merger talks.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Balfour Beatty was concerned that it would not receive what it considered the full value for Parsons Brinckerhoff if a deal with Carillion fell apart.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On Wednesday, Balfour Beatty said that it believed it could sell Parsons Brinckerhoff for âan attractive valueâ and return up to Â£200 million in capital to shareholders as a result.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">WSP Global, a Canadian professional services firm, is the frontrunner in the process to acquire Parsons Brinckerhoff, according to a person familiar with the matter.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Balfour Beatty, founded in 1909, provides construction, engineering and facilities management services in more than 80 countries. It reported revenue of Â£10.1 billion in 2013.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Carillion, created in 1999 by a spinoff from the Tarmac Group, primarily operates in Britain, Canada, the Middle East and North Africa. It posted revenue of Â£4.1 billion in 2013.</p>
